{"title_page": "Gemunu Kulatunge", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Gemunu Kulatunge\n|birth_date= \n|death_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=  [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears=1963-1996            \n|rank=[[Major General]]\n|branch= [[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=[[Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Deputy Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army \n|unit=[[Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment]]\n|battles= [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]],<br /> [[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br /> [[1987-89 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987-89]]\n|awards=[[Rana Sura Padakkama]],<br /> [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Major General]] '''Gemunu Kulatunge''', [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[National Defence College, India|ndc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]] (1941-2003) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n [[general]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Hashim |first=Ahmed |year=2013 |title=When Counterinsurgency Wins: Sri Lanka's Defeat of the Tamil Tigers |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]] |page=106 |isbn=9780812244526}}</ref> who was the former Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Sri Lanka Army]].\n\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]], he graduated from the [[University of Ceylon]] in 1960 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (Honours) degree and had won university colours for Rugby. He thereafter joined the [[Ceylon Army]]. Having completed his basic officer training at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Center, Diyatalawa]] and was commissioned into the [[Ceylon Sinha Regiment]] as a [[Second Lieutenant]] on 1 September 1965. He was posted to the 1st Battalion, Ceylon Sinha Regiment from April 1966, in which he served as a platoon commander, [[adjutant]]. He then served as company commander, [[staff officer]] II at the Army Training Center; staff officer II at [[Army Headquarters (Sri Lanka)|Army Headquarters]]. During the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] he was appointed [[military coordinating officer]], [[Kilinochchi District]]. Promoted to [[Lieutenant Colonel]], he was appointed [[Commanding Officer]], 1st Battalion, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment. He served as [[Commandant]],  Army Training School, Maduru Oya; Deputy Brigade Commander, 22 Brigade, Trincomalee; military coordinating officer, Matara; [[Brigade Commander]], 12 Brigade; Military Coordinating Officer, Kandy; Brigade Commander, 7 Brigade, Elephant Pass; Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters \u2013 Jaffna]]; Principal Staff Officer to [[Ministry_of_Defence_(Sri_Lanka)#Permanent_Secretaries|Secretary Defence]], Operational Headquarters, [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]]; Commander Task Force-Vavuniya; [[Adjutant General]], Army Headquarters; [[Overall Operational Command|Operations Commander Colombo]] and [[Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army]]. General Kulatunge is a graduate of the [[National Defence College, India]] . He was awarded the [[Rana Sura Padakkama]] (RSP), [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]] (USP), the [[Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal]], the [[Riviresa Campaign Services Medal]], the [[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]] and the [[North and East Operations Medal]]. He retired from the army in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maj. Gen. Gemunu Kulathunga (retd) bids adieu |url=http://www.army.lk/news/maj-gen-gemunu-kulathunga-retd-bids-adieu |website=army.lk |publisher=[[Sri Lanka Army]] |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Jungle Telegraph |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/961013/jungle.html |accessdate=19 October 2019 |publisher=Sundaytimes}}</ref> \n\nHe was married to Shirani Kulathunge, they had three children. Their son Shewanth Kulatunge, is a [[Colonel]] in the [[Sri Lanka Engineers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obituaries: June 27 (Monday) |url=http://www.timeslanka.com/category/in-memoriam/page/14/ |accessdate=19 October 2019 |publisher=Times Lanka}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Senior Army Colonel Passes MA in Strategic Security Studies with Flying Colours |url=https://www.army.lk/news/senior-army-colonel-passes-ma-strategic-security-studies-flying-colours |website=army.lk |publisher=[[Sri Lanka Army]] |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box | title=Deputy Chief of Staff\n | before= \n | after= | years=1995 - 1996}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kulatunge, Gemunu}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Sinha Regiment officers]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Gemunu Kulatunge\n|birth_date= \n|death_date= \n|birth_place= \n|death_place=\n|placeofburial= \n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= {{flagicon|Sri Lanka}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n|serviceyears=1963-1996            \n|rank=[[Major General]]\n|branch= [[Sri Lanka Army]]\n|commands=[[Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Deputy Chief of Staff]] of the Sri Lankan Army \n|unit=[[Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment]]\n|battles= [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]],<br /> [[Sri Lankan Civil War]],<br /> [[1987-89 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|Insurrection 1987-89]]\n|awards=[[Rana Sura Padakkama]],<br /> [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]]\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Major General]] '''Gemunu Kulatunge''', [[Rana Sura Padakkama|RSP]], [[Uttama Seva Padakkama|USP]], [[National Defence College, India|ndc]], [[psc (British Army)|psc]] (1941-2003) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n [[general]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Hashim |first=Ahmed |year=2013 |title=When Counterinsurgency Wins: Sri Lanka's Defeat of the Tamil Tigers |publisher=[[University of Pennsylvania Press]] |page=106 |isbn=9780812244526}}</ref> who was the former Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Sri Lanka Army]].\n\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]], he graduated from the [[University of Ceylon]] in 1960 with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] (Honours) degree and had won university colours for Rugby. He thereafter joined the [[Ceylon Army]]. Having completed his basic officer training at the [[Sri Lanka Military Academy|Army Training Center, Diyatalawa]] and was commissioned into the [[Ceylon Sinha Regiment]] as a [[Second Lieutenant]] on 1 September 1965. He was posted to the 1st Battalion, Ceylon Sinha Regiment from April 1966, in which he served as a platoon commander, [[adjutant]]. He then served as company commander, [[staff officer]] II at the Army Training Center; staff officer II at [[Army Headquarters (Sri Lanka)|Army Headquarters]]. During the [[1971 JVP Insurrection (Sri Lanka)|1971 Insurrection]] he was appointed [[military coordinating officer]], [[Kilinochchi District]]. Promoted to [[Lieutenant Colonel]], he was appointed [[Commanding Officer]], 1st Battalion, Sri Lanka Sinha Regiment. He served as [[Commandant]],  Army Training School, Maduru Oya; Deputy Brigade Commander, 22 Brigade, Trincomalee; military coordinating officer, Matara; [[Brigade Commander]], 12 Brigade; Military Coordinating Officer, Kandy; Brigade Commander, 7 Brigade, Elephant Pass; Commander, [[Security Forces Headquarters \u2013 Jaffna]]; Principal Staff Officer to [[Ministry_of_Defence_(Sri_Lanka)#Permanent_Secretaries|Secretary Defence]], Operational Headquarters, [[Ministry of Defence (Sri Lanka)|Ministry of Defence]]; Commander Task Force-Vavuniya; [[Adjutant General]], Army Headquarters; [[Overall Operational Command|Operations Commander Colombo]] and [[Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army (Sri Lanka)|Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army]]. General Kulatunge is a graduate of the [[National Defence College, India]] . He was awarded the [[Rana Sura Padakkama]] (RSP), [[Uttama Seva Padakkama]] (USP), the [[Sri Lanka Armed Services Long Service Medal]], the [[Riviresa Campaign Services Medal]], the [[Purna Bhumi Padakkama]] and the [[North and East Operations Medal]]. He retired from the army in 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Maj. Gen. Gemunu Kulathunga (retd) bids adieu |url=http://www.army.lk/news/maj-gen-gemunu-kulathunga-retd-bids-adieu |website=army.lk |publisher=[[Sri Lanka Army]] |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Jungle Telegraph |url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/961013/jungle.html |accessdate=19 October 2019 |publisher=Sundaytimes}}</ref> \n\nHe was married to Shirani Kulathunge, they had three children. Their son Shewanth Kulatunge, is a [[Colonel]] in the [[Sri Lanka Engineers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Obituaries: June 27 (Monday) |url=http://www.timeslanka.com/category/in-memoriam/page/14/ |accessdate=19 October 2019 |publisher=Times Lanka}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Senior Army Colonel Passes MA in Strategic Security Studies with Flying Colours |url=https://www.army.lk/news/senior-army-colonel-passes-ma-strategic-security-studies-flying-colours |website=army.lk |publisher=[[Sri Lanka Army]] |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{succession box | title=Deputy Chief of Staff\n | before= \n | after= | years=1995 - 1996}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kulatunge, Gemunu}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan generals]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Military Academy graduates]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese military personnel]]\n[[Category:Sinha Regiment officers]]\n", "name_user": "Dan arndt", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove flagicon from infobox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gemunu_Kulatunge"}
